pullRequest.body:
Adds the algebra instance on the `I`-adic completion of a ring `R`. Also provides the `AdicCompletion I R`-module instance on `AdicCompletion I M` for every `R`-module `M`. 

Co-authored-by: Judith Ludwig <ludwig@mathi.uni-heidelberg.de>

```suggestion
theorem transitionMap_map_mul {m n : â„•} (hmn : m â‰¤ n) (x y : R â§¸ (I ^ n â€¢ âŠ¤ : Ideal R)) :
    transitionMap I R hmn (x * y) = transitionMap I R hmn x * transitionMap I R hmn y :=
  Quotient.inductionOnâ‚‚' x y (fun _ _ â†¦ rfl)
```
`Quotient.inductionOnâ‚‚'` is designed for these situations.

```suggestion
def subalgebra : Subalgebra R (âˆ€ n, R â§¸ (I ^ n â€¢ âŠ¤ : Ideal R)) :=
  Submodule.toSubalgebra (submodule I R) (fun _ â†¦ by simp)
    (fun x y hx hy m n hmn â†¦ by simp [hx hmn, hy hmn])
```

```suggestion
/- No `simp` attribute, since it causes `simp` unification timeouts when considering
```

We usually write this kind of test as examples (we don't want them in the docs). Something like
```lean
example : module I = @Algebra.toModule (AdicCompletion I R)
  (AdicCompletion I R) _ _ (Algebra.id _) := rfl
```
Two comments:
* are these the two instantes you want to compare? It's better to write them like this than using `â€¢` (we check all the structures at once).
* `rfl` works, but the real test is `by with_reducible rfl` which *does not* work (the difference is that `by with_reducible rfl` does not unfold definitions that are not marked `reducible)`. I am not 100% sure to understand all the subtleties, but this probably means that for Lean those are not exactly the same. @eric-wieser  will this be a problem?
Yes, I think these are the instances I wanted to compare.
@eric-wieser do you think this is OK?
I don't know if it helps, but `by with_reducible_and_instances rfl` works. I just updated the PR.
Ah, I see, that's OK I think.
Do you mean "In the past, it had", or "Designed to have"

Ah right, it is not very clear as written. I want to say that we introduce this slightly weird `SMul` instance of `R â§¸ (I â€¢ âŠ¤)` on `M â§¸ (I â€¢ âŠ¤)` (instead of using the already existing `R â§¸ I`-module instance) to have good definitional behaviour.
So maybe "This is used to" instead of "Used to"?
